article.description: Michael Finley scored 23 points, including a key jumper with two minutes left, as the Dallas Mavericks extended their winning streak to eight games with a 108-99 victory over the Sacramento Kings.
article.headline: Finley, Mavs wear down West rivals

images.name: Nash Steve 040125 inline 195x262
images.caption: Steve Nash and the Mavs have the floor: eight straight wins after going back to back vs. the Lakers and now the Kings.

article.linkText: Mavs shoot down Kings, win 8th straight
article.story:
DALLAS (AP) -- The Dallas Mavericks have won eight straight games, and the latest victory means the most. Michael Finley scored 23 points, including the go-ahead 18-footer with 1:58 left, and the Mavericks won 108-99 Sunday over the Sacramento Kings, who entered with the Western Conference's best record. After Sacramento (30-12) fought back from a 10-point deficit to tie the game at 97 on Mike Bibby's 3-pointer with 2:14 left, the Mavericks scored nine straight points to clinch the victory. Finley's shot put the Mavericks ahead, and after a Kings miss, Steve Nash passed to Dirk Nowitzki for a layup and then added the free throw to put the Mavericks over 100 points with 1:28 to go. Dallas' season-long winning streak included a rare win Thursday over the injury-riddled Los Angeles Lakers, who were without Shaquille O'Neal, Kobe Bryant and Karl Malone. The Kings were without Chris Webber, but he's been out all season with a knee injury. The last seven wins have come since Mavericks owner Mark Cuban met with Don Nelson to clear the air about rumors concerning the coach's future. Nash had 21 points and a season-high 13 assists, with just one turnover. Nowitzki had 20 points and 12 rebounds. The Mavericks led by just one going into the fourth quarter, but the Kings missed their first nine shots. During that stretch, Dallas pushed the lead to 87-77 on Antoine Walker's slam dunk to end his string of seven straight points. Walker finished with 17 points. Bobby Jackson hit consecutive 3-pointers to tie the game at 94. After Walker hit another 3-pointer for the Mavericks, Bibby's 3-pointer tied the game for the last time. Peja Stojakovic led Sacramento with 24 points and 10 rebounds. Doug Christie had 23 points, while Jackson had 18. Brad Miller had 11 points and 17 rebounds. Sacramento, which lost at Memphis on Friday, had lost consecutive games only two other times. The last time was when they lost at home on Christmas Day to Dallas, and then at Golden State the next night. A strange sequence started a 9-2 run late in the second quarter that put Sacramento back ahead. The teams traded turnovers and missed shots, with Jackson leaping over first-row spectators trying to save a loose ball. While play continued and Dallas missed a shot, Jackson got back on the floor and was wide open to take Anthony Peeler's pass for an easy layup. Nowitzki then had a steal and got the ball back for a slam before the Kings scored seven straight to go ahead 41-40 on Christie's layup. The Mavs were back in front at halftime, 50-47.

Game notes
In the last 19 regular-season games between the Kings and Mavericks, the top two scoring teams in the league, at least one team has scored 100 points. Both had broken the century mark in 12 of them. ... Antawn Jamison played in his 290th straight game, the league's longest active streak. He had 13 points and 10 rebounds. ... The Mavericks had their 94th straight sellout. ... The Kings are 10-2 in Sunday games.
